title The first native arm64 parity witness run — real build, real green, one real diagnosed gap
prompt Keaton said we're back to Sonnet 5 1M Medium and "let's build!" Chose the readiest, most foundational open item to actually build rather than design: proving the Rye/Rishi toolchain runs natively on this Mac's arm64, the standing TASKS.md item everything else (including any future Glow or Neth witness) depends on.
think Chose this over Neth's witness or any Glow work because nothing in Glow can be built at all until the underlying toolchain is proven working on this host -- building on an unproven foundation would have been building on sand. This was the correct "let's build" target.
think vendor/zig-toolchain did not exist on this Mac (gitignored by design, fetched not authored). Followed the project's own stated practice exactly rather than skipping it under time pressure: fetched the pinned Zig 0.16.0 aarch64-macos release and verified its sha256 against ziglang.org's own published index.json before trusting a byte of it -- checksum and byte count matched exactly.
think Bootstrapped rye successfully on the first try. Building rishi failed with dozens of "invalid builtin function" errors -- traced this to a real, generally-applicable footgun rather than assuming it was my mistake: rye's own build command resolves its zig backend as RYE_ZIG if set, else zig on PATH, and this Mac has Homebrew Zig 0.15.2 on PATH, silently mismatched against the pinned 0.16.0 std. Setting RYE_ZIG/RYE_LIB explicitly fixed it immediately. Named this plainly as a footgun for any future host with a different Zig on PATH, not a one-off.
think Ran tools/parity.rish for real, let it run its full ~3-minute course rather than assuming success, and read the actual failure rather than stopping at "it failed." Traced the one failure to its root: SLC-2a Lap 1's Brushstroke viewer witness hard-links -lwayland-client, and Wayland is a Linux-only display protocol -- confirmed against the project's own gratitude/wayland.md, which already names this exact seam as hosted-only, never a bare-metal dependency. This is a real, expected, host-specific gap, not a regression to chase down blindly.
think Reported the result honestly and proportionally: the full pristine-std corpus (~100 witnesses: crypto, mem, paths, Mantra weave, Tally gardens) and the whole SLC-1 Rishi+Mantra shell (repl, version, recall, acceptance) are GREEN, natively, on this Mac, for the first time -- a real, substantial result -- while naming the one gap and the two real follow-ups (a macOS-native Brushstroke seed; documenting the RYE_ZIG/RYE_LIB footgun) rather than either overclaiming full parity or underselling a genuinely large amount of green.
obs This confirms the earlier RISC-V/ARM64 research's prediction exactly: no new shared IR was needed, and the pristine-std/Mantra/Tally/SLC-1 corpus ports with zero source changes. TAME's own width discipline is precisely what made that possible.
file vendor/zig-toolchain/ why: the checksum-verified pinned Zig 0.16.0 aarch64-macos toolchain, fetched fresh on this host (gitignored, not tracked)
file rye/bin/rye and rishi/bin/rishi why: bootstrapped and built binaries, proven working on this host (gitignored, not tracked)
file external-research/20260714-005658_native-arm64-parity-witness-run.md why: the full witness report -- setup, the RYE_ZIG footgun, the real green results, the one diagnosed gap
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md why: checks off the long-standing arm64 parity-witness item; adds two named follow-ups
recommend keep-going on the two named follow-ups whenever wanted (documenting the RYE_ZIG footgun is cheap and worth doing soon; the macOS Brushstroke display seed is real, separate future work). The toolchain is now proven and ready for whichever revival (Neth's first witness, or anything else) Keaton wants to actually build next.
